<h1 id="advantages-and-disadvantages-of-relational-databases-rdbms-and-nosql-databases">Advantages and Disadvantages of Relational Databases (RDBMS) and NoSQL Databases</h1>
<hr />
<h2 id="relational-databases-rdbms">Relational Databases (RDBMS)</h2>
<p>Examples: MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, Microsoft SQL Server</p>
<h3 id="advantages">Advantages</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li>Strong Data Integrity (ACID Compliance)
<ul>
<li>Provides Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability (ACID).<br />
</li>
<li>Ensures reliable transactions and consistent data, essential for financial systems or enterprise applications.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Structured Data and Relationships
<ul>
<li>Data is stored in tables with predefined schemas.<br />
</li>
<li>Relationships between entities are managed through foreign keys for referential integrity.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Powerful Query Capabilities (SQL)
<ul>
<li>SQL supports complex queries, joins, and data aggregation.<br />
</li>
<li>SQL is standardized and widely understood.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Data Accuracy and Validations
<ul>
<li>Constraints (unique keys, check constraints) enforce data quality and prevent duplication.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Mature Ecosystem and Support
<ul>
<li>Established tools, documentation, and reliability.</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h3 id="disadvantages">Disadvantages</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li>Limited Horizontal Scalability
<ul>
<li>Designed for vertical scaling (adding hardware power) rather than horizontal scaling (adding more nodes).<br />
</li>
<li>Challenging with massive, distributed workloads.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Rigid Schema (Less Flexibility)
<ul>
<li>Altering tables or relationships can require downtime or complex migrations.<br />
</li>
<li>Not suitable when data models change frequently.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Performance Limitations with Big Data
<ul>
<li>Managing large datasets with many relationships can slow down joins and queries.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Not Ideal for Unstructured Data
<ul>
<li>Best suited for structured data, not for media, logs, or JSON-based unstructured information.</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2 id="nosql-databases">NoSQL Databases</h2>
<p>Examples: MongoDB, Cassandra, Redis, Couchbase, DynamoDB, Neo4j</p>
<h3 id="advantages-1">Advantages</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li>Schema Flexibility (Schema-less Design)
<ul>
<li>No predefined structure required.<br />
</li>
<li>Ideal for frequently changing or unstructured data (e.g., user profiles, IoT).</li>
</ul></li>
<li>High Scalability (Horizontal Scaling)
<ul>
<li>Designed for distributed, cloud-first architectures.<br />
</li>
<li>Easy capacity expansion by distributing data across servers.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>High Performance and Speed
<ul>
<li>Optimized for fast reads/writes and low latency.<br />
</li>
<li>Ideal for real-time analytics, streaming, or social media.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Variety of Data Models
<ul>
<li>Supports multiple paradigms:
<ul>
<li>Document-based (MongoDB) → flexible JSON documents<br />
</li>
<li>Key-value stores (Redis) → fast lookups<br />
</li>
<li>Wide column stores (Cassandra) → analytics and large-scale data<br />
</li>
<li>Graph databases (Neo4j) → networked data and relationships</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li>High Availability and Fault Tolerance
<ul>
<li>Data replication and sharding ensure reliability even with node failures.</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h3 id="disadvantages-1">Disadvantages</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li>Eventual Consistency (Weaker Guarantees)
<ul>
<li>Scalability and speed may reduce immediate consistency; updates may not instantly propagate to all nodes.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>No Unified Query Language
<ul>
<li>Different NoSQL systems use different syntaxes or APIs.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Limited Multi-Record Transactions
<ul>
<li>Complex multi-record transactions may not be fully ACID-compliant.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Less Mature Ecosystem
<ul>
<li>Fewer standardized management and optimization tools compared to RDBMS.</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
